timental entertainment depended on sensational effects that produced surprise, horror, and even gales of laughter. After the Civil War the sensational charge became more important than the sentimental bond, and new forms of entertainment gained in popularity and provided the foundations for vaudeville, America’s first mass entertainment. Ultimately, it was American entertainment’s variety that would provide the true soul of pleasure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAmusementsxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aAmusementszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPerforming artsxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aPerforming artszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPopular culturexHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aPopular culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 4aPerforming Arts & Drama. 4aRecreation. 4aU.S. History.  apopular culture, entartainment, sentimentality, theater, performances.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2016z9783110485189oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170399740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501703997423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501703997/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DEGb2016  aZDB-23-DGGb2016